	<entry>
		<title>By: Eli Weinstock-Herman (tarwn)</title>
		<link rel="alternate" href="/index.php/management/how-i-hire-developers/#comment-4865321" type="text/html" />

		<author>
			<name>Eli Weinstock-Herman (tarwn)</name>
			
		</author>

		<id>/?p=4159#comment-4865321</id>
		<updated>2016-01-07T00:31:20Z</updated>
		<published>2016-01-07T00:31:20Z</published>
		<content type="html" xml:base="/index.php/management/how-i-hire-developers/#comment-4865321"><![CDATA[<p>For me, the technical screen is a tool to help identify whether the candidate meets a low technical bar. I try not to assume that not meeting that bar is a result of them being a &#8220;bad apple&#8221; because it could also just as easily be due to misplaced enthusiasm about their own skill level or because they are actually fairly senior but felt that a simple technical problem required a full enterprise architecture or, the opposite, didn&#8217;t require a readable answer.</p>
]]></content>
		<thr:in-reply-to ref="/?p=4159#comment-4850987" href="/index.php/management/how-i-hire-developers/#comment-4850987" type="text/html" />
	</entry>
	<entry>
